        <!-- Project Overview -->
        <div class="project-section">
            <h3>Project Overview</h3>
            <p>
                This project demonstrates deploying a <strong>WordPress application</strong> on AWS EC2 using two approaches:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Manual provisioning</strong> via AWS Console + SSH.</li>
                <li><strong>Automated provisioning</strong> using AWS CloudFormation (Infrastructure as Code).</li>
            </ul>
            <p>The goal was to compare the traditional console-based setup with automation through IaC.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Architecture -->
        <div class="project-section alt-bg">
            <h3>Architecture Explanation</h3>
            <p>The architecture includes the following components:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>User Browser</strong> – Accesses the WordPress site via HTTP (port 80).</li>
                <li><strong>Admin (SSH)</strong> – Connects securely on port 22 using a key pair.</li>
                <li><strong>VPC & Public Subnet</strong> – Default VPC environment where the EC2 instance resides.</li>
                <li><strong>Internet Gateway</strong> – Enables internet access to the EC2 instance.</li>
                <li><strong>EC2 Instance (Ubuntu Linux)</strong> – Hosts Apache, PHP, WordPress, and MySQL (all on the same instance).</li>
                <li><strong>EBS Volume</strong> – Persistent storage for OS, WordPress files, and MySQL database.</li>
                <li><strong>Security Group</strong> – Firewall allowing SSH (22) and HTTP (80).</li>
                <li><strong>CloudFormation Stack</strong> – Automates provisioning and configuration.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Key Learnings -->
        <div class="project-section">
            <h3>Key Learnings</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Launched and configured an EC2 instance via AWS Console.</li>
                <li>Used SSH key pairs for secure administration.</li>
                <li>Installed and configured the LAMP stack for WordPress hosting.</li>
                <li>Experienced the difference between manual setup vs IaC automation.</li>
                <li>Learned how IaC improves repeatability and reduces setup time.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Best Practices -->
        <div class="project-section alt-bg">
            <h3>Notes & Best Practices</h3>
            <p>
                In this project, all components (web server, PHP, WordPress, and MySQL) were deployed on a single EC2 instance for simplicity.
                This is fine for learning or small-scale demos, but in production:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>The database is typically hosted separately on Amazon RDS for reliability and scalability.</li>
                <li>Media files can be stored on S3 with CloudFront CDN for better performance.</li>
                <li>A Load Balancer with Auto Scaling ensures high availability and traffic handling.</li>
                <li>SSH access should be restricted to trusted IPs only.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>


